**Sec. 20001. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources for improving the quality of life for military personnel.**

This section appropriates $7.8 billion for various quality-of-life improvements for military personnel, including $1 billion for military housing, $2.9 billion for housing allowances, $100 million for child care fee assistance, and $100 million for tuition assistance. It also temporarily increases the investment limit in privatized military housing projects from 33.3% to 60% and extends the authority for acquisition or construction of privatized military unaccompanied housing until 2029.

**Sec. 20002. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources for shipbuilding.**

This section allocates $12.5 billion for various shipbuilding initiatives, including $4.6 billion for a second Virginia-class submarine, $5.4 billion for two additional Guided Missile Destroyers, and $2.7 billion for the procurement of T-AO oilers. It also funds the development and production of unmanned surface and underwater vessels, as well as improvements to shipbuilding industrial base capabilities.

**Sec. 20003. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources for integrated air and missile defense.**

This section appropriates $20.5 billion for missile defense and air defense systems, including $5.6 billion for space-based and boost phase intercept capabilities, $2.2 billion for hypersonic defense systems, and $2.5 billion for missile defense capabilities. It also funds the development of directed energy capabilities and the expansion of missile defense radars.

**Sec. 20004. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources for munitions and defense supply chain resiliency.**

This section allocates $12.5 billion for munitions and supply chain resiliency initiatives, including $4.6 billion for missile production and integration, $1 billion for solid rocket motor industrial base investments, and $500 million for the production of Navy long-range air and missile defense interceptors. It also funds the development of alternative munitions and the expansion of defense manufacturing techniques.

**Sec. 20005. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources for scaling low-cost weapons into production.**

This section appropriates $6.5 billion for scaling low-cost weapons into production, including $1.4 billion for the expansion of the small unmanned aerial system industrial base, $1 billion for the acceleration of innovative military logistics and energy capability development, and $2 billion for the expansion of the Defense Innovation Unit scaling of commercial technology for military use.

**Sec. 20006. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources for improving the efficiency and cybersecurity of the Department of Defense.**

This section allocates $480 million for improving the efficiency and cybersecurity of the Department of Defense, including $150 million for business systems replacement, $200 million for the deployment of automation and artificial intelligence, and $20 million for defense cybersecurity programs.

**Sec. 20007. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources for air superiority.**

This section appropriates $6.5 billion for air superiority initiatives, including $3.1 billion for increasing F-15EX aircraft production, $1.1 billion for the development, procurement, and integration of Air Force long-range strike aircraft, and $500 million for the development, procurement, and integration of Navy long-range strike aircraft.

**Sec. 20008. Enhancement of resources for nuclear forces.**

This section allocates $11.5 billion for nuclear forces, including $2.5 billion for risk reduction activities for the Sentinel intercontinental ballistic missile program, $4.5 billion for the expansion of B-21 long-range bomber aircraft production, and $1 billion for the development, procurement, and integration of the nuclear-armed sea-launched cruise missile.

**Sec. 20009. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources to improve capabilities of United States Indo-Pacific Command.**

This section appropriates $12.5 billion for improving the capabilities of the United States Indo-Pacific Command, including $3.6 billion for the development, procurement, and integration of United States military satellites, $1 billion for offensive cyber operations, and $1.1 billion for the development of infrastructure within the Indo-Pacific Command area of operations.

**Sec. 20010. Enhancement of Department of Defense resources for improving the readiness of the Department of Defense.**

This section allocates $12.5 billion for improving the readiness of the Department of Defense, including $2.5 billion for Air Force facilities sustainment, restoration, and modernization, $1.5 billion for Army depot modernization and capacity enhancement, and $1 billion for National Guard unit readiness.

**Sec. 20011. Improving Department of Defense border support and counter-drug missions.**

This section appropriates $1 billion for the deployment of military personnel in support of border operations, counter-narcotics, and counter-transnational criminal organization missions.

**Sec. 20012. Department of Defense oversight.**

This section appropriates $10 million for the Inspector General of the Department of Defense to monitor Department of Defense activities funded in this title, focusing on programs with mutual technological dependencies, data management considerations, and supply chain vulnerabilities.

**Sec. 20013. Military construction projects authorized.**

This section authorizes the appropriation of funds for military construction, land acquisition, and military family housing functions of each military department, requiring the Secretary of each military department to submit a detailed spending plan by project for all funds made available by this title within 30 days of the enactment of this title. [end of text]


